1,Array Methods,What does Array.isArray() do?,,Array.isArray() checks whether an object is an array; returns true or false.,"const testArray = [1, 2, 3];
Array.isArray(testArray)
// returns true",https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Array/isArray,,,
2,Array Methods,"What does Array.reduce() look like, what does it do, and how does it work?",,"Array.reduce() reduce the values of an array to a single value, from left-to-right.
Accumulator holds the sum as the function iterates through an array.
currentValue adds the next index position to the sum / accumulator.
initialValue specifies where the count starts from; usually 0.
,const array = [1, 2, 3, 4];
const initialValue = 0;
const sumWithInitial = array.reduce(
(accumulator, currentValue) => accumulator + currentValue,
initialValue
console.log(sumWithInitial);
// Expected output: 10",https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Array/reduce,,,
3,Array Methods,What does Array.toString() do?,,"Array.toString() converts an array to a string, and returns the result.
A similar result can be obtained with .join().","const array1 = [1, 2, 'a', '1a'];
console.log(array1.toString());
// Expected output: ""1,2,a,1a""",https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Array/toString,,,
4,Array Methods,What does Array.some() do?,,Array.some() checks if any of the elements in an array pass a test.,"const array = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5];
// Checks whether an element is even
const even = (element) => element % 2 === 0;
console.log(array.some(even));
// Expected output: true",https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Array/some,,,
5,Array Methods,What does Array.from() do?,,Array.from() creates an array from an object.,"console.log(Array.from('foo'));
// Expected output: Array [""f"", ""o"", ""o""]
console.log(Array.from([1, 2, 3], x => x + x));
// Expected output: Array [2, 4, 6]",https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Array/from,,,
6,Array Methods,What does Array.unshift() do?,,"Array.unshift() adds new elements to the beginning of an array, and returns the new length.","const array = [1, 2, 3];
array.unshift(4, 5);
// returns new array length: 5
console.log(array);
const otherArray = [6, 7, 8, 9, 10];
array.unshift(...otherArray);
// returns new array length: 10;
console.log(array);
// returns array: [6, 7, 8, 9, 10, 4, 5, 1, 2, 3]",https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Array/unshift,,,
7,Array Methods,What does Array.shift() do?,,"Array.shift() removes the first element of an array, and returns that element. Shift = Start.","const array = [1, 2, 3, 4];
array.shift();
// returns: 1
console.log(array);
// returns: Array [2, 3, 4]
const firstElement = array.shift();
// calling array.shift to assign to firstElement removes first element
console.log(array);
// Expected output: Array [3, 4]
console.log(firstElement);
// returns: 2",https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Array/shift,,,
8,Array Methods,What does Array.indexOf() do?,,Array.indexOf() search the array for an element and returns its position as an integer.,"const beasts = ['ant', 'bison', 'camel', 'duck', 'bison'];
console.log(beasts.indexOf('bison'));
// Expected output: 1
// Start from index 2
console.log(beasts.indexOf('bison', 2));
// Expected output: 4
console.log(beasts.indexOf('giraffe'));
// Expected output: -1",https://www.google.com/search?q=Array.indexOf(),,,

9,Array Methods,What does Array.lastIndexOf() do?,,"Array.lastIndexOf() searches an array for an element, starting at the end, and returns its position.","const animals = ['Dodo', 'Tiger', 'Penguin', 'Dodo'];
console.log(animals.lastIndexOf('Dodo'));
// Expected output: 3
console.log(animals.lastIndexOf('Tiger'));
// Expected output: 1",https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Array/lastIndexOf,,,
10,Boolean Methods,What does Boolean.toString() do?,,"Boolean.toString() converts a boolean value to a string, and returns the result.","const flag1 = new Boolean(true);
console.log(flag1.toString());
// Expected output: ""true""
const flag2 = new Boolean(1);
console.log(flag2.toString());
// Expected output: ""true""",https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Boolean/toString,,,

11,Array Methods,What does Array.keys() do?,,"Array.keys() returns a Array Iteration object that contains the keys for each index in the array. In the provided example, 'keys' are essentially numerical index positions.","const array = ['a', 'b', 'c'];
const iterator = array.keys();
for (const key of iterator) {
console.log(key);
// Expected output: 0
// Expected output: 1
// Expected output: 2",https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Array/keys,,,

299,Methods 2,What does Rest parameters (...args) do?,,"
A function can be called with any number of arguments even if that function has excessive arguments than originally defined. But the ones that are defined will be the only ones that are counted.
allows us to represent an indefinite number of arguments as an array. this is how we get an array from a list of parameters
Use case: to create functions that accept any number of arguments
function sum(...theArgs) {
return theArgs.reduce((previous, current) => {
return previous + current;
console.log(sum(1, 2, 3));
// expected output: 6
console.log(sum(1, 2, 3, 4));
// expected output: 10",,https://www.google.com/search?q=Rest parameters (...args),,,
300,Methods 2,What does Spread syntax do?,,"- UNPACKS/SPREADS the collected items into single elements
- can be used in conjunction w normal values, multiple iterables like (...arr1, ...arr2))
- can also be used to MERGE arrays
- can be used to turn string into array of characters
Use case:
- pass an array into functions that normally require a list of many arguments
allows an iterable (like an array or string) to be EXPANDED in places where 0 or more:
- arguments or elements are expected (for functions)
- elements (for array literals)
- object expression for more key-value pairs (for object literals)
function sum(x, y, z) {
return x + y + z;
const numbers = [1, 2, 3];
console.log(sum(...numbers));
// expected output: 6
console.log(sum.apply(null, numbers));
// expected output: 6",,https://www.google.com/search?q=Spread syntax,,,
